-- ACTS CHAPTER 7 — Stephen's Defense: Israel's History of Resistance and God's Unfolding Plan
-- 60 verses · Original text · Word studies · Cross-refs
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- Step 1: Insert chapter metadata
INSERT INTO chapters (book_id, chapter_number, overview, theme, key_word_original, key_word_meaning, outline)
SELECT b.id, 7,
  'Acts Chapter 7 records Stephen''s powerful and lengthy defense before the Sanhedrin, a speech that ultimately leads to his martyrdom. Stephen recounts the history of Israel from Abraham to Solomon, emphasizing God''s presence outside the temple and the recurring pattern of Israel''s rebellion against God''s chosen leaders and prophets. He highlights key figures like Abraham, Joseph, and Moses, demonstrating how God worked through them despite Israel''s resistance. The speech culminates in a scathing indictment of his accusers, labeling them ''stiffnecked'' and ''uncircumcised in heart and ears'' for resisting the Holy Spirit and persecuting the prophets, ultimately betraying and murdering ''the Just One,'' Jesus Christ. This chapter is crucial for understanding early Christian apologetics, the continuity of God''s redemptive plan, and the profound theological shift from temple-centric worship to Christ-centered faith.',
  'Stephen''s Defense: Israel''s History of Resistance and God''s Unfolding Plan',
  'ἀντιπίπτω (antipiptō)',
  'Derived from ''anti'' (against) and ''piptō'' (to fall), meaning ''to fall against,'' ''to resist,'' or ''to oppose.'' In Acts 7:51, Stephen uses it to describe Israel''s persistent rebellion against God''s Spirit and His messengers throughout their history, culminating in their rejection of Jesus. It signifies a willful, stubborn opposition to divine truth and authority.',
  '["Section 1 (vv.1-8): Abraham and the Covenant of Promise","Section 2 (vv.9-16): Joseph and the Patriarchs in Egypt","Section 3 (vv.17-29): Moses'' Birth, Education, and Initial Rejection","Section 4 (vv.30-43): Moses'' Commission, Deliverance, and Israel''s Rebellion in the Wilderness","Section 5 (vv.44-50): The Tabernacle, Temple, and God''s Transcendent Presence","Section 6 (vv.51-53): Stephen''s Indictment of the Sanhedrin","Section 7 (vv.54-60): Stephen''s Vision and Martyrdom"]'
FROM books b WHERE b.name = 'Acts';

-- Step 2: Insert all 60 verses
INSERT INTO verses (chapter_id, verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
SELECT c.id, v.verse_number, v.kjv_text, v.original_text, v.transliteration, v.study_note, v.doctrinal_note
FROM chapters c
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  (1,
   'Then said the high priest, Are these things so?',
   'Εἶπεν δὲ ὁ ἀρχιερεύς, Εἰ ἄρα ταῦτα οὕτως ἔχει;',
   'Eipen de ho archiereus, Ei ara tauta houtōs echei?',
   'This verse marks the beginning of Stephen''s defense. The high priest''s question, ''Are these things so?'' (KJV), is a direct inquiry into the accusations leveled against Stephen concerning blasphemy against Moses, God, the temple, and the Law (Acts 6:11-14). Stephen''s response is not a simple ''yes'' or ''no,'' but a comprehensive historical narrative designed to demonstrate God''s consistent work through His chosen people, often in ways that challenged their preconceived notions of sacred space and tradition.',
   NULL),
  (2,
   'And he said, Men, brethren, and fathers, hearken; The God of glory appeared unto our father Abraham, when he was in Mesopotamia, before he dwelt in Charran,',
   'Ὁ δὲ ἔφη, Ἄνδρες ἀδελφοὶ καὶ πατέρες, ἀκούσατε. Ὁ Θεὸς τῆς δόξης ὤφθη τῷ πατρὶ ἡμῶν Ἀβραὰμ ὄντι ἐν τῇ Μεσοποταμίᾳ, πρὶν ἢ κατοικῆσαι αὐτὸν ἐν Χαρράν,',
   'Ho de ephē, Andres adelphoi kai pateres, akousate. Ho Theos tēs doxēs ōphthē tō patri hēmōn Abraam onti en tē Mesopotamiā, prin ē katoikēsai auton en Charrān,',
   'Stephen begins his defense by addressing the Sanhedrin with respect (''Men, brethren, and fathers''). He immediately establishes God''s initiative in salvation history, emphasizing that ''The God of glory'' appeared to Abraham in Mesopotamia, *before* he settled in Haran (Charran). This detail is significant as it subtly challenges the idea that God''s presence is confined to a specific land or temple, showing God''s activity in a ''pagan'' land. This sets the stage for Stephen''s later arguments about God''s omnipresence.',
   'Stephen''s opening highlights God''s sovereignty and initiative in salvation history. The ''God of glory'' (ὁ Θεὸς τῆς δόξης) emphasizes His majestic and transcendent nature, revealing Himself to Abraham not in a temple, but in a foreign land. This underscores that God''s covenant relationship with humanity predates and is not limited by human institutions or geographical boundaries, laying a foundation for a broader understanding of God''s work.'),
  (3,
   'And said unto him, Get thee out of thy country, and from thy kindred, and come into the land which I shall shew thee.',
   'καὶ εἶπεν αὐτῷ, Ἔξελθε ἐκ τῆς γῆς σου καὶ ἐκ τῆς συγγενείας σου, καὶ δεῦρο εἰς τὴν γῆν ἣν ἄν σοι δείξω.',
   'kai eipen autō, Exelthe ek tēs gēs sou kai ek tēs syngeneias sou, kai deuro eis tēn gēn hēn an soi deixō.',
   'This verse quotes God''s command to Abraham from Genesis 12:1. Stephen emphasizes Abraham''s obedience to God''s call to leave his homeland and kindred. The phrase ''the land which I shall shew thee'' highlights the element of faith required, as Abraham did not know the destination beforehand. This act of leaving a familiar place for an unknown one, solely based on God''s promise, serves as a foundational example of faith for Stephen''s audience.',
   'God''s call to Abraham demonstrates the principle of divine election and the necessity of faith-filled obedience. Abraham''s willingness to leave his familiar surroundings based solely on God''s promise illustrates radical trust in God''s leading. This call initiates the covenant relationship that forms the basis of Israel''s identity, emphasizing that their existence as a people is rooted in God''s sovereign choice and their ancestor''s response of faith.'),
  (4,
   'Then came he out of the land of the Chaldaeans, and dwelt in Charran: and from thence, when his father was dead, he removed him into this land, wherein ye now dwell.',
   'Τότε ἐξελθὼν ἐκ γῆς Χαλδαίων κατῴκησεν ἐν Χαρράν· κἀκεῖθεν μετὰ τὸ ἀποθανεῖν τὸν πατέρα αὐτοῦ μετῴκισεν αὐτὸν εἰς τὴν γῆν ταύτην εἰς ἣν ὑμεῖς νῦν κατοικεῖτε.',
   'Tote exelthōn ek gēs Chaldaion katōikēsen en Charrān; kakeithen meta to apothanein ton patera autou metōikisen auton eis tēn gēn tautēn eis hēn hymeis nyn katoikeite.',
   'Stephen clarifies Abraham''s journey, stating he first left the ''land of the Chaldaeans'' (Ur of the Chaldees) and dwelt in Haran. Crucially, he notes that God moved Abraham into the promised land ''when his father was dead.'' This detail, consistent with Genesis 11:32 and 12:4, highlights Abraham''s full separation from his ancestral ties before entering Canaan, underscoring the completeness of his obedience and God''s timing. The phrase ''this land, wherein ye now dwell'' directly connects their present reality to God''s ancient promise.',
   NULL),
  (5,
   'And he gave him none inheritance in it, no, not so much as to set his foot on: yet he promised that he would give it to him for a possession, and to his seed after him, when as yet he had no child.',
   'καὶ οὐκ ἔδωκεν αὐτῷ κληρονομίαν ἐν αὐτῇ οὐδὲ βῆμα ποδός, καὶ ἐπηγγείλατο δοῦναι αὐτῷ εἰς κατάσχεσιν αὐτὴν καὶ τῷ σπέρματι αὐτοῦ μετ’ αὐτόν, οὐκ ὄντος αὐτῷ τέκνου.',
   'kai ouk edōken autō klēronomian en autē oude bēma podos, kai epēngeilato dounai autō eis kataschesin autēn kai tō spermati autou met'' auton, ouk ontos autō teknou.',
   'Stephen emphasizes that Abraham received ''none inheritance'' in the land, ''no, not so much as to set his foot on.'' This detail underscores the nature of God''s promise as a matter of faith, not immediate possession. Despite having no child, God promised the land to Abraham and his ''seed after him.'' This highlights God''s faithfulness to His promises even when human circumstances seem to contradict them, a theme central to God''s dealings with Israel.',
   'This verse powerfully illustrates the nature of God''s promises and the role of faith. Abraham received no immediate inheritance, yet he believed God''s promise of future possession for his descendants. This emphasizes that God''s covenant blessings are often realized progressively and require enduring faith, even in the absence of immediate tangible evidence. It points to a spiritual reality beyond present circumstances.'),
  (6,
   'And God spake on this wise, That his seed should sojourn in a strange land; and that they should bring them into bondage, and entreat them evil four hundred years.',
   'ἐλάλησεν δὲ οὕτως ὁ Θεός, ὅτι ἔσται τὸ σπέρμα αὐτοῦ πάροικον ἐν γῇ ἀλλοτρίᾳ, καὶ δουλώσουσιν αὐτὸ καὶ κακώσουσιν ἔτη τετρακόσια.',
   'elalēsen de houtōs ho Theos, hoti estai to sperma autou paroikon en gē allotriā, kai doulōsousin auto kai kakōsousin etē tetrakosia.',
   'Stephen recounts God''s prophecy to Abraham (Genesis 15:13) that his descendants would be ''sojourn[ers] in a strange land'' and suffer ''bondage'' and ''evil entreat[ment]'' for ''four hundred years.'' This demonstrates God''s foreknowledge and control over history, even over periods of suffering for His people. It also sets up the narrative of deliverance through Moses, which Stephen will elaborate on, showing God''s consistent intervention.',
   NULL),
  (7,
   'And the nation to whom they shall be in bondage will I judge, said God: and after that shall they come forth, and serve me in this place.',
   'καὶ τὸ ἔθνος ᾧ ἐὰν δουλεύσουσιν κρινῶ ἐγώ, εἶπεν ὁ Θεός· καὶ μετὰ ταῦτα ἐξελεύσονται καὶ λατρεύσουσίν μοι ἐν τῷ τόπῳ τούτῳ.',
   'kai to ethnos hō ean douleusousin krinō egō, eipen ho Theos; kai meta tauta exeleusontai kai latreusousin moi en tō topō toutō.',
   'Continuing the prophecy from Genesis 15:14, Stephen highlights God''s promise to judge the oppressive nation (Egypt) and bring His people out to ''serve me in this place.'' This foreshadows the Exodus and the giving of the Law at Mount Sinai, emphasizing God''s justice and His ultimate purpose for His people: worship and service. The phrase ''in this place'' likely refers to the land of Canaan, or more broadly, the place of God''s choosing for worship.',
   'This verse underscores God''s justice and redemptive purpose. He not only foresees the suffering of His people but also promises to judge their oppressors and deliver them for the purpose of worship and service. This reveals God''s active involvement in human history, demonstrating His faithfulness to His covenant promises and His ultimate desire for a people who will serve Him.'),
  (8,
   'And he gave him the covenant of circumcision: and so Abraham begat Isaac, and circumcised him the eighth day; and Isaac begat Jacob; and Jacob begat the twelve patriarchs.',
   'καὶ ἔδωκεν αὐτῷ διαθήκην περιτομῆς· καὶ οὕτως ἐγέννησεν τὸν Ἰσαὰκ καὶ περιέτεμεν αὐτὸν τῇ ἡμέρᾳ τῇ ὀγδόῃ, καὶ Ἰσαὰκ τὸν Ἰακώβ, καὶ Ἰακὼβ τοὺς δώδεκα πατριάρχας.',
   'kai edōken autō diathēkēn peritomēs; kai houtōs egennēsen ton Isaak kai perietemen auton tē hēmerā tē ogdoē, kai Isaak ton Iakōb, kai Iakōb tous dōdeka patriarchas.',
   'Stephen mentions the ''covenant of circumcision'' given to Abraham (Genesis 17), which became the physical sign of the covenant with God. He traces the lineage through Isaac, Jacob, and the ''twelve patriarchs,'' establishing the continuity of God''s covenant people. This detail is important because circumcision was a central tenet of Jewish identity, and Stephen''s accusers likely valued it highly. By affirming its origin, Stephen shows his respect for their heritage while preparing to challenge their understanding of its true significance.',
   'The covenant of circumcision served as a physical sign of God''s covenant with Abraham and his descendants, marking them as His chosen people. This verse highlights the continuity of God''s covenant faithfulness through generations, from Abraham to the twelve patriarchs. While a physical sign, its deeper meaning pointed to a spiritual separation and dedication to God, a concept Stephen will later expand upon regarding ''circumcision of the heart'' (v. 51).'),
  (9,
   'And the patriarchs, moved with envy, sold Joseph into Egypt: but God was with him,',
   'καὶ οἱ πατριάρχαι ζηλώσαντες τὸν Ἰωσὴφ ἀπέδοντο εἰς Αἴγυπτον· καὶ ἦν ὁ Θεὸς μετ’ αὐτοῦ,',
   'kai hoi patriarchai zēlōsantes ton Iōsēph apedonto eis Aigypton; kai ēn ho Theos met'' autou,',
   'Stephen introduces the story of Joseph, noting that the patriarchs, ''moved with envy,'' sold him into Egypt (Genesis 37). This immediately highlights a pattern of internal conflict and rejection within Israel''s history, a subtle parallel to Stephen''s own situation. Crucially, he adds, ''but God was with him,'' emphasizing God''s sovereign presence and purpose even amidst human sin and betrayal. This theme of God working through rejected figures is central to Stephen''s argument.',
   'This verse introduces the theme of rejection and divine sovereignty. The patriarchs'' envy and betrayal of Joseph foreshadow Israel''s later rejection of God''s chosen leaders and prophets, including Jesus. Yet, God''s presence ''with him'' (Joseph) demonstrates that divine purposes are not thwarted by human sin, but rather God works through adverse circumstances to fulfill His plan, turning evil into good (Gen 50:20).'),
  (10,
   'And delivered him out of all his afflictions, and gave him favour and wisdom in the sight of Pharaoh king of Egypt; and he made him governor over Egypt and all his house.',
   'καὶ ἐξείλετο αὐτὸν ἐκ πασῶν τῶν θλίψεων αὐτοῦ, καὶ ἔδωκεν αὐτῷ χάριν καὶ σοφίαν ἐναντίον Φαραὼ βασιλέως Αἰγύπτου, καὶ κατέστησεν αὐτὸν ἡγούμενον ἐπ’ Αἴγυπτον ὅλην καὶ ἐφ’ ὅλον τὸν οἶκον αὐτοῦ.',
   'kai exeileto auton ek pasōn tōn thlipseōn autou, kai edōken autō charin kai sophian enantion Pharaō basileōs Aigyptou, kai katestēsen auton hēgoumenon ep'' Aigypton holēn kai eph'' holon ton oikon autou.',
   'Stephen continues Joseph''s story, detailing God''s deliverance from ''all his afflictions'' and granting him ''favour and wisdom'' before Pharaoh. This led to Joseph''s elevation as ''governor over Egypt and all his house'' (Genesis 41:37-43). This narrative illustrates how God can exalt the rejected and use them for His purposes, not only for their own good but for the salvation of many, including Joseph''s own family. This serves as a powerful type of Christ.',
   NULL),
  (11,
   'Now there came a dearth over all the land of Egypt and Chanaan, and great affliction: and our fathers found no sustenance.',
   'Ἦλθεν δὲ λιμὸς ἐφ’ ὅλην τὴν γῆν Αἰγύπτου καὶ Χαναάν, καὶ θλῖψις μεγάλη· καὶ οὐχ ηὕρισκον χορτάσματα οἱ πατέρες ἡμῶν.',
   'Ēlthen de limos eph'' holēn tēn gēn Aigyptou kai Chanaan, kai thlipsis megalē; kai ouch heuriskon chortasmata hoi pateres hēmōn.',
   'Stephen recounts the famine that struck Egypt and Canaan (Genesis 41:56-57), leading to ''great affliction'' and a lack of ''sustenance'' for ''our fathers.'' This detail emphasizes the dire circumstances that necessitated Joseph''s position and the subsequent migration of Jacob''s family to Egypt. It highlights God''s providential hand in orchestrating events to fulfill His promises and preserve His people.',
   NULL),
  (12,
   'But when Jacob heard that there was corn in Egypt, he sent out our fathers first.',
   'ἀκούσας δὲ Ἰακὼβ ὄντα σιτία ἐν Αἰγύπτῳ ἐξαπέστειλεν τοὺς πατέρας ἡμῶν πρῶτον.',
   'akousas de Iakōb onta sitia en Aigyptō exapesteilen tous pateras hēmōn prōton.',
   'Jacob, hearing of ''corn in Egypt,'' sent his sons (Stephen''s ''fathers'') there for the first time (Genesis 42:1-2). This action initiates the reunion with Joseph and the eventual relocation of the entire family to Egypt, fulfilling aspects of God''s prophecy to Abraham (v. 6). Stephen''s detailed recounting of these familiar stories serves to remind his audience of their own history and God''s consistent working through it.',
   NULL),
  (13,
   'And at the second time Joseph was made known to his brethren; and Joseph’s kindred was made known unto Pharaoh.',
   'καὶ ἐν τῷ δευτέρῳ Ἰωσὴφ ἀνεγνωρίσθη τοῖς ἀδελφοῖς αὐτοῦ, καὶ φανερὸν ἐγένετο τῷ Φαραὼ τὸ γένος Ἰωσήφ.',
   'kai en tō deuterō Iōsēph anegnōristhē tois adelphois autou, kai phaneron egeneto tō Pharaō to genos Iōsēph.',
   'Stephen notes that ''at the second time'' Joseph was made known to his brethren (Genesis 45:1-4), and his ''kindred was made known unto Pharaoh.'' This recognition is a pivotal moment in the narrative, leading to reconciliation and the preservation of Jacob''s family. The ''second time'' motif might subtly foreshadow Jesus'' second coming or the second opportunity for Israel to recognize their Messiah.',
   NULL),
  (14,
   'Then sent Joseph, and called his father Jacob to him, and all his kindred, threescore and fifteen souls.',
   'ἀποστείλας δὲ Ἰωσὴφ μετεκαλέσατο Ἰακὼβ τὸν πατέρα αὐτοῦ καὶ πᾶσαν τὴν συγγένειαν ἐν ψυχαῖς ἑβδομήκοντα πέντε.',
   'aposteilas de Iōsēph metekalesato Iakōb ton patera autou kai pasan tēn syngeneian en psychais hebdomēkonta pente.',
   'Joseph sent for his father Jacob and ''all his kindred, threescore and fifteen souls'' (Genesis 45:9-10; 46:27). Stephen''s number ''seventy-five'' differs from the Masoretic Text''s ''seventy'' (Genesis 46:27; Exodus 1:5), but aligns with the Septuagint (LXX) reading (Genesis 46:27; Exodus 1:5; Deuteronomy 10:22). This demonstrates Stephen''s familiarity with the Greek Old Testament, which was commonly used by Hellenistic Jews in the diaspora.',
   NULL),
  (15,
   'So Jacob went down into Egypt, and died, he, and our fathers,',
   'καὶ κατέβη Ἰακὼβ εἰς Αἴγυπτον, καὶ ἐτελεύτησεν αὐτὸς καὶ οἱ πατέρες ἡμῶν,',
   'kai katebē Iakōb eis Aigypton, kai eteleutēsen autos kai hoi pateres hēmōn,',
   'Jacob and ''our fathers'' went down to Egypt and died there (Genesis 46:5-7; 49:33). This marks the end of the patriarchal period and the beginning of the sojourn in Egypt, as prophesied to Abraham (v. 6). Stephen''s concise summary moves the narrative forward, setting the stage for the subsequent period of oppression and the rise of Moses.',
   NULL),
  (16,
   'And were carried over into Sychem, and laid in the sepulchre that Abraham bought for a sum of money of the sons of Emmor the father of Sychem.',
   'καὶ μετετέθησαν εἰς Συχὲμ καὶ ἐτέθησαν ἐν τῷ μνήματι ᾧ ὠνήσατο Ἀβραὰμ τιμῆς ἀργυρίου παρὰ τῶν υἱῶν Ἐμμὸρ τοῦ Συχέμ.',
   'kai metetethēsan eis Sychem kai etethēsan en tō mnēmati hō ōnēsato Abraam timēs argyriou para tōn huiōn Emmor tou Sychem.',
   'Stephen states that Jacob and the patriarchs were carried to ''Sychem'' (Shechem) and laid in the sepulchre that Abraham bought from the ''sons of Emmor.'' This verse presents a textual difficulty, as Genesis 50:13 states Jacob was buried in the cave of Machpelah (Hebron), which Abraham bought from Ephron the Hittite (Genesis 23). Joshua 24:32 states Joseph''s bones were buried in Shechem in a plot Jacob bought. Stephen might be conflating these traditions or referring to a different purchase by Abraham, or perhaps ''Abraham'' is used metonymically for the patriarchs. The main point is the burial in the promised land, emphasizing their connection to it.',
   NULL),
  (17,
   'But when the time of the promise drew nigh, which God had sworn to Abraham, the people grew and multiplied in Egypt,',
   'Καθὼς δὲ ἤγγιζεν ὁ χρόνος τῆς ἐπαγγελίας ἧς ὤμοσεν ὁ Θεὸς τῷ Ἀβραάμ, ηὔξησεν ὁ λαὸς καὶ ἐπληθύνθη ἐν Αἰγύπτῳ,',
   'Kathōs de ēggizen ho chronos tēs epangelias hēs ōmosen ho Theos tō Abraam, ēuxēsen ho laos kai eplēthynthē en Aigyptō,',
   'As the ''time of the promise'' (the 400 years of sojourning and affliction) drew near, the people ''grew and multiplied in Egypt'' (Exodus 1:7). This highlights God''s faithfulness to His promise to Abraham that his seed would become a great nation (Genesis 12:2). The growth of Israel in Egypt, despite their bondage, demonstrates God''s power to fulfill His word even in challenging circumstances, setting the stage for their miraculous deliverance.',
   'This verse emphasizes God''s faithfulness to His covenant promises. Despite the harsh conditions of slavery, God caused Abraham''s descendants to multiply in Egypt, fulfilling His oath. This demonstrates divine sovereignty over demographic and historical processes, ensuring that His redemptive plan progresses according to His timing and word, even when human circumstances seem to contradict it.'),
  (18,
   'Till another king arose, which knew not Joseph.',
   'ἄχρι οὗ ἀνέστη βασιλεὺς ἕτερος ἐπ’ Αἴγυπτον, ὃς οὐκ ᾔδει τὸν Ἰωσήφ.',
   'achri hou anestē basileus heteros ep'' Aigypton, hos ouk ēdei ton Iōsēph.',
   'Stephen introduces the ''another king'' who ''knew not Joseph'' (Exodus 1:8). This new Pharaoh initiated the oppression of the Israelites, marking a significant shift in their status from favored guests to enslaved laborers. This historical detail underscores the transient nature of human favor and the need for divine intervention, preparing the audience for the story of Moses, God''s chosen deliverer.',
   NULL),
  (19,
   'The same dealt subtilly with our kindred, and evil entreated our fathers, so that they cast out their young children, to the end they might not live.',
   'οὗτος κατασοφισάμενος τὸ γένος ἡμῶν ἐκάκωσεν τοὺς πατέρας, τοῦ ποιεῖν ἔκθετα τὰ βρέφη αὐτῶν εἰς τὸ μὴ ζωογονεῖσθαι.',
   'houtos katasophisamenos to genos hēmōn ekakōsen tous pateras, tou poiein ektheta ta brephē autōn eis to mē zōogoneisthai.',
   'This Pharaoh ''dealt subtilly'' with Israel and ''evil entreated our fathers,'' commanding the exposure of their male infants to prevent their survival (Exodus 1:9-22). This act of genocide highlights the extreme oppression faced by the Israelites and the desperate circumstances into which Moses was born. Stephen''s recounting of this suffering would resonate with his Jewish audience, reminding them of God''s past deliverance from such tyranny.',
   NULL),
  (20,
   'In which time Moses was born, and was exceeding fair, and nourished up in his father’s house three months:',
   'ἐν ᾧ καιρῷ ἐγεννήθη Μωϋσῆς, καὶ ἦν ἀστεῖος τῷ Θεῷ· ὃς ἀνετράφη ἐν τῷ οἴκῳ τοῦ πατρὸς ἐπὶ μῆνας τρεῖς.',
   'en hō kairō egennēthē Mōysēs, kai ēn asteios tō Theō; hos anetraphē en tō oikō tou patros epi mēnas treis.',
   'Stephen introduces Moses, born during this time of intense persecution. He describes Moses as ''exceeding fair'' (KJV) or ''beautiful to God'' (ἀστεῖος τῷ Θεῷ), a phrase also found in the Septuagint (Exodus 2:2). This divine favor from birth sets Moses apart. His initial nurturing in his father''s house for three months (Exodus 2:2) highlights the efforts made to preserve him against Pharaoh''s decree, foreshadowing his special role.',
   NULL),
  (21,
   'And when he was cast out, Pharaoh’s daughter took him up, and nourished him for her own son.',
   'καὶ ἐκτεθέντος αὐτοῦ ἀνείλετο αὐτὸν ἡ θυγάτηρ Φαραὼ καὶ ἀνεθρέψατο αὐτὸν ἑαυτῇ εἰς υἱόν.',
   'kai ekthethentos autou aneileto auton hē thugatēr Pharaō kai anethrepsato auton heautē eis huion.',
   'When Moses was ''cast out'' (exposed), Pharaoh''s daughter rescued him and ''nourished him for her own son'' (Exodus 2:5-10). This miraculous preservation and adoption into the royal household are crucial. It demonstrates God''s providential care, placing His chosen deliverer within the very court of the oppressor, where he would gain the knowledge and skills necessary for his future mission.',
   'This event showcases God''s remarkable providence, using an unexpected agent (Pharaoh''s daughter) to preserve and raise His chosen deliverer within the very system he was destined to challenge. It illustrates that God''s plans are often accomplished through extraordinary and seemingly contradictory means, demonstrating His sovereign control over all circumstances, even those orchestrated by His enemies.'),
  (22,
   'And Moses was learned in all the wisdom of the Egyptians, and was mighty in words and in deeds.',
   'καὶ ἐπαιδεύθη Μωϋσῆς ἐν πάσῃ σοφίᾳ Αἰγυπτίων, ἦν δὲ δυνατὸς ἐν λόγοις καὶ ἔργοις αὐτοῦ.',
   'kai epaideuthē Mōysēs en pasē sophiā Aigyptiōn, ēn de dynatos en logois kai ergois autou.',
   'Moses was ''learned in all the wisdom of the Egyptians'' and ''was mighty in words and in deeds.'' This detail, not explicitly stated in Exodus but affirmed by Jewish tradition (e.g., Josephus, Philo), emphasizes Moses'' exceptional qualifications. He possessed both intellectual prowess and practical ability, making him a formidable leader. This background would have been recognized by Stephen''s audience as a mark of greatness, yet Stephen will show how even this prepared leader faced rejection.',
   NULL),
  (23,
   'And when he was full forty years old, it came into his heart to visit his brethren the children of Israel.',
   'Ὡς δὲ ἐπληροῦτο αὐτῷ τεσσαρακονταετής χρόνος, ἀνέβη ἐπὶ τὴν καρδίαν αὐτοῦ ἐπισκέψασθαι τοὺς ἀδελφοὺς αὐτοῦ τοὺς υἱοὺς Ἰσραήλ.',
   'Hōs de eplērouto autō tessarakontaetēs chronos, anebē epi tēn kardian autou episkepsasthai tous adelphous autou tous huios Israēl.',
   'When Moses was ''full forty years old,'' he felt compelled to ''visit his brethren the children of Israel'' (Exodus 2:11). This marks a turning point, as Moses, despite his Egyptian upbringing, identified with his Hebrew heritage. This act of ''visiting'' signifies a desire to understand and perhaps alleviate their suffering, demonstrating a nascent sense of his calling, though not yet fully understood.',
   NULL),
  (24,
   'And seeing one of them suffer wrong, he defended him, and avenged him that was oppressed, and smote the Egyptian:',
   'καὶ ἰδών τινα ἀδικούμενον ἠμύνατο, καὶ ἐποίησεν ἐκδίκησιν τῷ καταπονουμένῳ πατάξας τὸν Αἰγύπτιον.',
   'kai idōn tina adikoumenon ēmynato, kai epoiēsen ekdikēsin tō kataponoumenō pataxas ton Aigyption.',
   'Moses'' intervention to defend an Israelite suffering wrong, by striking and killing an Egyptian (Exodus 2:11-12), is presented as an act of avenging the oppressed. This impulsive act, though born of a desire for justice, also reveals Moses'' premature attempt to deliver his people, using human strength rather than waiting for God''s divine timing and method. It highlights the human element in God''s plan.',
   NULL),
  (25,
   'For he supposed his brethren would have understood how that God by his hand would deliver them: but they understood not.',
   'ἐνόμιζεν δὲ συνιέναι τοὺς ἀδελφοὺς αὐτοῦ ὅτι ὁ Θεὸς διὰ χειρὸς αὐτοῦ δίδωσιν σωτηρίαν αὐτοῖς· οἱ δὲ οὐ συνῆκαν.',
   'enomizen de synienai tous adelphous autou hoti ho Theos dia cheiros autou didōsin sōtērian autois; hoi de ou synēkan.',
   'Stephen makes a crucial interpretive point: Moses ''supposed his brethren would have understood how that God by his hand would deliver them: but they understood not.'' This highlights the initial rejection of Moses by his own people, who failed to recognize God''s chosen deliverer. This theme of rejection, particularly of God''s appointed leaders, is a recurring motif in Stephen''s speech and serves as a direct parallel to the Sanhedrin''s rejection of Jesus.',
   'This verse introduces a profound theological theme: the rejection of God''s chosen deliverer by His own people. Moses'' expectation that his brethren would ''understand'' God''s hand in his actions underscores divine intention, yet their failure to comprehend reveals a spiritual blindness. This foreshadows Israel''s later rejection of Jesus, ''the Just One'' (v. 52), and serves as a direct indictment of Stephen''s audience, who similarly failed to recognize God''s ultimate deliverer.'),
  (26,
   'And the next day he shewed himself unto them as they strove, and would have set them at one again, saying, Sirs, ye are brethren; why do ye wrong one to another?',
   'Τῇ τε ἐπιούσῃ ἡμέρᾳ ὤφθη αὐτοῖς μαχομένοις, καὶ συνήλασεν αὐτοὺς εἰς εἰρήνην εἰπών, Ἄνδρες, ἀδελφοί ἐστε· ἵνα τί ἀδικεῖτε ἀλλήλους;',
   'Tē te epiousē hēmerā ōphthē autois machomenois, kai synēlasen autous eis eirēnēn eipōn, Andres, adelphoi este; hina ti adikeite allēlous?',
   'The next day, Moses attempted to reconcile two fighting Israelites, appealing to their shared brotherhood: ''Sirs, ye are brethren; why do ye wrong one to another?'' (Exodus 2:13). This act shows Moses'' desire for peace and unity among his people. However, his attempt at mediation is met with further rejection, reinforcing the pattern of Israel''s resistance to those God sends to help them.',
   NULL),
  (27,
   'But he that did his neighbour wrong thrust him away, saying, Who made thee a ruler and a judge over us?',
   'ὁ δὲ ἀδικῶν τὸν πλησίον ἀπώσατο αὐτὸν εἰπών, Τίς σε κατέστησεν ἄρχοντα καὶ δικαστὴν ἐφ’ ἡμῶν;',
   'ho de adikōn ton plēsion apōsato auton eipōn, Tis se katestēsen archonta kai dikastēn eph'' hēmōn?',
   'The Israelite who was doing wrong ''thrust him away,'' challenging Moses'' authority with the question, ''Who made thee a ruler and a judge over us?'' (Exodus 2:14). This direct rejection of Moses'' leadership is a critical point in Stephen''s narrative. It highlights Israel''s unwillingness to accept God''s chosen leader, even when he sought their good. This question directly parallels the Sanhedrin''s challenge to Jesus'' authority and, implicitly, to Stephen''s own authority as a Spirit-filled messenger.',
   'This verse powerfully illustrates the human tendency to reject divinely appointed authority, especially when it challenges personal sin. The question ''Who made thee a ruler and a judge?'' echoes through history, reflecting humanity''s resistance to God''s chosen leaders and, ultimately, to Christ Himself. It underscores the theme of rejection that Stephen uses to indict his audience, showing a historical pattern of resisting God''s messengers.'),
  (28,
   'Wilt thou kill me, as thou diddest the Egyptian yesterday?',
   'Μὴ ἀνελεῖν με σὺ θέλεις ὃν τρόπον ἀνεῖλες ἐχθὲς τὸν Αἰγύπτιον;',
   'Mē aneilein me sy theleis hon tropon aneiles echthes ton Aigyption?',
   'The Israelite''s accusation, ''Wilt thou kill me, as thou diddest the Egyptian yesterday?'' (Exodus 2:14), reveals that Moses'' act of violence was known and feared. This public exposure of his deed forced Moses to flee. Stephen uses this detail to further emphasize Moses'' initial rejection and the circumstances that led to his forty-year exile in Midian, a period of preparation before his divine commission.',
   NULL),
  (29,
   'Then fled Moses at this saying, and was a stranger in the land of Madian, where he begat two sons.',
   'ἔφυγεν δὲ Μωϋσῆς ἐν τῷ λόγῳ τούτῳ, καὶ ἐγένετο πάροικος ἐν γῇ Μαδιάμ, οὗ ἐγέννησεν υἱοὺς δύο.',
   'ephygen de Mōysēs en tō logō toutō, kai egeneto paroikos en gē Madiam, hou egennēsen huios dyo.',
   'Moses ''fled'' because of this incident and became a ''stranger in the land of Madian'' (Midian), where he begat two sons (Exodus 2:15-22). This period of exile, lasting forty years, was a time of humbling and preparation for Moses. It demonstrates that God often prepares His chosen instruments in obscurity before calling them to public service, refining their character and teaching them dependence on Him.',
   NULL),
  (30,
   'And when forty years were expired, there appeared to him in the wilderness of mount Sina an angel of the Lord in a flame of fire in a bush.',
   'Καὶ πληρωθέντων ἐτῶν τεσσαράκοντα ὤφθη αὐτῷ ἐν τῇ ἐρήμῳ τοῦ ὄρους Σινᾶ ἄγγελος Κυρίου ἐν φλογὶ πυρὸς βάτου.',
   'Kai plērōthentōn etōn tessarakonta ōphthē autō en tē erēmō tou orous Sina angelos Kyriou en phlogi pyros batou.',
   'After ''forty years'' in Midian, ''an angel of the Lord'' appeared to Moses ''in the wilderness of mount Sina'' (Sinai) in a ''flame of fire in a bush'' (Exodus 3:1-2). This divine encounter marks Moses'' official commissioning. Stephen''s emphasis on the ''angel of the Lord'' is significant, as it highlights the role of angels in mediating God''s presence and revelation, a point he will later use to critique the Jewish understanding of the Law (v. 53).',
   'This pivotal event marks God''s direct intervention and commissioning of Moses. The appearance of the ''angel of the Lord'' in the burning bush signifies God''s holy presence and His intention to deliver His people. It demonstrates that God reveals Himself not only in sacred spaces but also in the wilderness, underscoring His transcendence and active involvement in human history, preparing His chosen instrument for a monumental task.'),
  (31,
   'When Moses saw it, he wondered at the sight: and as he drew near to behold it, the voice of the LORD came unto him,',
   'ὁ δὲ Μωϋσῆς ἰδὼν ἐθαύμασεν τὸ ὅραμα· προσερχομένου δὲ αὐτοῦ κατανοῆσαι ἐγένετο φωνὴ Κυρίου πρὸς αὐτόν,',
   'ho de Mōysēs idōn ethaumasen to horama; proserchomenou de autou katanoēsai egeneto phōnē Kyriou pros auton,',
   'Moses ''wondered at the sight'' of the burning bush, and as he drew near to examine it, ''the voice of the LORD came unto him'' (Exodus 3:3-4). This highlights the awe-inspiring nature of God''s presence and the direct communication between God and Moses. It underscores the divine origin of Moses'' authority and mission, which Stephen is carefully establishing for his audience.',
   NULL),
  (32,
   'Saying, I am the God of thy fathers, the God of Abraham, and the God of Isaac, and the God of Jacob. Then Moses trembled, and durst not behold.',
   'Ἐγὼ ὁ Θεὸς τῶν πατέρων σου, ὁ Θεὸς Ἀβραάμ καὶ Ἰσαὰκ καὶ Ἰακώβ. ἔντρομος δὲ γενόμενος Μωϋσῆς οὐκ ἐτόλμα κατανοῆσαι.',
   'Egō ho Theos tōn paterōn sou, ho Theos Abraam kai Isaak kai Iakōb. entromos de genomenos Mōysēs ouk etolma katanoēsai.',
   'God identifies Himself as ''the God of thy fathers, the God of Abraham, and the God of Isaac, and the God of Jacob'' (Exodus 3:6). This declaration links Moses'' mission directly to the covenant promises made to the patriarchs, establishing continuity in God''s redemptive plan. Moses'' trembling and inability to behold God''s presence emphasize the holiness and majesty of God, a reverence Stephen''s audience would understand.',
   'God''s self-identification as ''the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob'' affirms His covenant faithfulness across generations. This declaration, later used by Jesus (Matt 22:32) to prove the resurrection, underscores God''s enduring relationship with His people and the living nature of His covenant. Moses'' fear highlights the awe-inspiring holiness of God, demanding reverence and separation.'),
  (33,
   'Then said the Lord to him, Put off thy shoes from thy feet: for the place where thou standest is holy ground.',
   'Εἶπεν δὲ αὐτῷ ὁ Κύριος, Λῦσον τὸ ὑπόδημα τῶν ποδῶν σου· ὁ γὰρ τόπος ἐν ᾧ ἕστηκας γῆ ἁγία ἐστίν.',
   'Eipen de autō ho Kyrios, Lyson to hypodēma tōn podōn sou; ho gar topos en hō hestēkas gē hagia estin.',
   'God commands Moses to ''Put off thy shoes from thy feet: for the place where thou standest is holy ground'' (Exodus 3:5). This command signifies reverence and purification in the presence of God''s holiness. Stephen''s inclusion of this detail subtly prepares his audience for his later argument that God''s presence is not confined to the temple in Jerusalem, but can sanctify any place where He chooses to reveal Himself.',
   'The command to remove shoes signifies reverence and purification in the presence of divine holiness. This establishes the principle that God''s presence, not a man-made structure, sanctifies a place. This concept challenges a rigid, localized understanding of worship, foreshadowing Stephen''s argument that God ''dwelleth not in temples made with hands'' (v. 48) and that true worship transcends physical locations.'),
  (34,
   'I have seen, I have seen the affliction of my people which is in Egypt, and I have heard their groaning, and am come down to deliver them. And now come, I will send thee into Egypt.',
   'Ἰδὼν εἶδον τὴν κάκωσιν τοῦ λαοῦ μου τοῦ ἐν Αἰγύπτῳ, καὶ τοῦ στεναγμοῦ αὐτῶν ἤκουσα, καὶ κατέβην ἐξελέσθαι αὐτούς· καὶ νῦν δεῦρο, ἀποστελῶ σε εἰς Αἴγυπτον.',
   'Idōn eidon tēn kakōsin tou laou mou tou en Aigyptō, kai tou stenagmou autōn ēkousa, kai katebēn exelesthai autous; kai nyn deuro, apostelō se eis Aigypton.',
   'God declares His awareness of Israel''s suffering (''I have seen, I have seen the affliction'') and His intention to deliver them (''I have heard their groaning, and am come down to deliver them''). He then commissions Moses: ''And now come, I will send thee into Egypt'' (Exodus 3:7-10). This highlights God''s compassion, His active intervention in history, and His choice of Moses as the instrument of deliverance, despite Moses'' earlier rejection by his people.',
   'This verse powerfully illustrates God''s compassionate nature and His active involvement in human suffering. He ''sees'' and ''hears'' the cries of His people, demonstrating His empathy and commitment to justice. His declaration ''I am come down to deliver them'' underscores divine intervention in history and His sovereign power to rescue, establishing the foundation for His redemptive plan through chosen agents like Moses.'),
  (35,
   'This Moses whom they refused, saying, Who made thee a ruler and a judge? the same did God send to be a ruler and a deliverer by the hand of the angel which appeared to him in the bush.',
   'Τοῦτον τὸν Μωϋσῆν, ὃν ἠρνήσαντο εἰπόντες, Τίς σε κατέστησεν ἄρχοντα καὶ δικαστήν; τοῦτον ὁ Θεὸς ἄρχοντα καὶ λυτρωτὴν ἀπέσταλκεν σὺν χειρὶ ἀγγέλου τοῦ ὀφθέντος αὐτῷ ἐν τῇ βάτῳ.',
   'Touton ton Mōysēn, hon ērnēsanto eipontes, Tis se katestēsen archonta kai dikastēn? touton ho Theos archonta kai lytrōtēn apestalken syn cheiri angelou tou ophthentos autō en tē batō.',
   'Stephen draws a direct parallel: ''This Moses whom they refused, saying, Who made thee a ruler and a judge? the same did God send to be a ruler and a deliverer.'' This is a central point of his argument. Despite Israel''s initial rejection, God sovereignly appointed Moses as their ''ruler and a deliverer'' (ἄρχοντα καὶ λυτρωτὴν). The phrase ''by the hand of the angel'' reiterates the divine mediation in Moses'' commissioning, linking it back to the burning bush encounter.',
   'This verse is a powerful theological pivot, highlighting the paradox of divine election and human rejection. The very Moses whom Israel rejected, God appointed as ''ruler and deliverer.'' This pattern foreshadows Christ''s rejection by His own people, yet God''s sovereign plan of salvation proceeds through Him. It underscores that God''s chosen instruments derive their authority from Him, not from human acceptance.'),
  (36,
   'He brought them out, after that he had shewed wonders and signs in the land of Egypt, and in the Red sea, and in the wilderness forty years.',
   'οὗτος ἐξήγαγεν αὐτοὺς ποιήσας τέρατα καὶ σημεῖα ἐν γῇ Αἰγύπτῳ καὶ ἐν Ἐρυθρᾷ θαλάσσῃ καὶ ἐν τῇ ἐρήμῳ ἔτη τεσσαράκοντα.',
   'houtos exēgagen autous poiēsas terata kai sēmeia en gē Aigyptō kai en Erythrā thalassē kai en tē erēmō etē tessarakonta.',
   'Moses ''brought them out'' of Egypt, performing ''wonders and signs'' there, at the Red Sea, and ''in the wilderness forty years.'' This summarizes the Exodus and wilderness wanderings, emphasizing God''s miraculous power displayed through Moses. The ''forty years'' in the wilderness is a significant period of testing and formation for Israel, a time when they continued to resist God and His appointed leader.',
   NULL),
  (37,
   'This is that Moses, which said unto the children of Israel, A prophet shall the Lord your God raise up unto you of your brethren, like unto me; him shall ye hear.',
   'Οὗτός ἐστιν ὁ Μωϋσῆς ὁ εἰπὼν τοῖς υἱοῖς Ἰσραήλ, Προφήτην ὑμῖν ἀναστήσει Κύριος ὁ Θεὸς ὑμῶν ἐκ τῶν ἀδελφῶν ὑμῶν ὡς ἐμέ· αὐτοῦ ἀκούσεσθε.',
   'Houtos estin ho Mōysēs ho eipōn tois huiois Israēl, Prophētēn hymin anastēsei Kyrios ho Theos hymōn ek tōn adelphōn hymōn hōs eme; autou akousesthe.',
   'Stephen quotes Moses'' prophecy from Deuteronomy 18:15, 18, concerning a ''Prophet'' whom the Lord would raise up ''of your brethren, like unto me; him shall ye hear.'' This prophecy is universally understood by early Christians as referring to Jesus Christ. By quoting it, Stephen implicitly asserts that Jesus is the ultimate fulfillment of this prophecy, and by rejecting Jesus, his audience is rejecting Moses'' own words and God''s ultimate deliverer.',
   'This verse is a crucial Christological statement. Stephen identifies Jesus as the fulfillment of Moses'' prophecy of a ''Prophet like unto me.'' This establishes Jesus'' authority as the ultimate divine messenger and deliverer, surpassing Moses. The command ''him shall ye hear'' underscores the imperative to obey Christ, implying that rejection of Jesus is a rejection of God''s final word and a continuation of Israel''s historical pattern of disobedience.'),
  (38,
   'This is he, that was in the church in the wilderness with the angel which spake to him in the mount Sina, and with our fathers: who received the lively oracles to give unto us:',
   'οὗτός ἐστιν ὁ γενόμενος ἐν τῇ ἐκκλησίᾳ ἐν τῇ ἐρήμῳ μετὰ τοῦ ἀγγέλου τοῦ λαλοῦντος αὐτῷ ἐν τῷ ὄρει Σινᾶ καὶ τῶν πατέρων ἡμῶν, ὃς ἐδέξατο λόγια ζῶντα δοῦναι ἡμῖν·',
   'houtos estin ho genomenos en tē ekklēsiā en tē erēmō meta tou angelou tou lalountos autō en tō orei Sina kai tōn paterōn hēmōn, hos edexato logia zōnta dounai hēmin;',
   'Stephen refers to Moses as being ''in the church (ἐκκλησίᾳ) in the wilderness'' with the angel at Sinai and ''our fathers.'' The term ''church'' here refers to the assembly of Israel, highlighting the continuity of God''s people. Moses ''received the lively oracles (λόγια ζῶντα) to give unto us,'' referring to the Law. Stephen emphasizes the divine origin and life-giving nature of the Law, yet he will soon pivot to show Israel''s failure to obey it.',
   'This verse highlights the divine origin and life-giving nature of the Law, referred to as ''lively oracles'' (λόγια ζῶντα). It also uses ''ἐκκλησίᾳ'' (assembly/church) for Israel in the wilderness, suggesting a continuity of God''s covenant people from the Old Testament to the New. Moses, as the mediator of this Law, foreshadows Christ, the mediator of a new and living covenant, emphasizing the Law''s divine authority but also its preparatory role.'),
  (39,
   'To whom our fathers would not obey, but thrust him from them, and in their hearts turned back again into Egypt,',
   'ᾧ οὐκ ἠθέλησαν ὑπήκοοι γενέσθαι οἱ πατέρες ἡμῶν, ἀλλὰ ἀπώσαντο, καὶ ἐστράφησαν τῇ καρδίᾳ αὐτῶν εἰς Αἴγυπτον,',
   'hō ouk ēthelēsan hypēkooi genesthai hoi pateres hēmōn, alla apōsanto, kai estraphēsan tē kardiā autōn eis Aigypton,',
   'Stephen delivers a scathing indictment: ''To whom our fathers would not obey, but thrust him from them, and in their hearts turned back again into Egypt.'' This directly accuses Israel of rejecting Moses and, by extension, God''s Law. The phrase ''turned back again into Egypt'' signifies a spiritual apostasy, a desire to return to bondage and idolatry rather than embrace God''s freedom and covenant. This is a direct parallel to Stephen''s accusers, who are rejecting God''s new covenant in Christ.',
   'This verse presents a profound theological indictment: Israel''s persistent disobedience and spiritual apostasy. Their refusal to obey Moses and their desire to return to Egypt (''turned back again into Egypt'') reveal a deep-seated rebellion against God''s will and a preference for spiritual bondage over divine freedom. This historical pattern of rejecting God''s chosen leaders and His covenant serves as a powerful parallel to Stephen''s audience''s rejection of Christ.'),
  (40,
   'Saying unto Aaron, Make us gods to go before us: for as for this Moses, which brought us out of the land of Egypt, we wot not what is become of him.',
   'εἰπόντες τῷ Ἀαρών, Ποίησον ἡμῖν θεοὺς οἳ προπορεύσονται ἡμῶν· ὁ γὰρ Μωϋσῆς οὗτος, ὃς ἐξήγαγεν ἡμᾶς ἐκ γῆς Αἰγύπτου, οὐκ οἴδαμεν τί ἐγένετο αὐτῷ.',
   'eipontes tō Aarōn, Poiēson hēmin theous hoi proporeusontai hēmōn; ho gar Mōysēs houtos, hos exēgagen hēmas ek gēs Aigyptou, ouk oidamen ti egeneto autō.',
   'Stephen recounts the golden calf incident (Exodus 32:1, 23), where the people demanded Aaron, ''Make us gods to go before us: for as for this Moses, which brought us out of the land of Egypt, we wot not what is become of him.'' This act of idolatry, committed shortly after receiving the Law, epitomizes their rebellion and impatience. It underscores their tendency to replace God''s invisible presence with tangible idols, a critique Stephen implicitly extends to their reliance on the physical temple.',
   NULL),
  (41,
   'And they made a calf in those days, and offered sacrifice unto the idol, and rejoiced in the works of their own hands.',
   'καὶ ἐμοσχοποίησαν ἐν ἐκείναις ταῖς ἡμέραις, καὶ ἀνήγαγον θυσίαν τῷ εἰδώλῳ, καὶ εὐφραίνοντο ἐν τοῖς ἔργοις τῶν χειρῶν αὐτῶν.',
   'kai emoschopoiēsan en ekeinais tais hēmerais, kai anēgagon thysian tō eidōlō, kai euphrainonto en tois ergois tōn cheirōn autōn.',
   'The Israelites ''made a calf in those days, and offered sacrifice unto the idol, and rejoiced in the works of their own hands'' (Exodus 32:4-6). This vivid description of idolatry highlights their self-worship and rejection of the true God. Stephen''s emphasis on ''works of their own hands'' is a subtle but powerful critique, suggesting that their reliance on man-made religious structures (like the temple) and traditions mirrors this ancient idolatry.',
   'This verse exposes the essence of idolatry: worshipping ''the works of their own hands.'' It reveals humanity''s propensity to create gods in their own image or to rely on human achievements rather than on the living God. This historical example serves as a warning against any form of self-reliance or misplaced worship, subtly critiquing the Sanhedrin''s potential over-reliance on the physical temple and their own traditions.'),
  (42,
   'Then God turned, and gave them up to worship the host of heaven; as it is written in the book of the prophets, O ye house of Israel, have ye offered to me slain beasts and sacrifices by the space of forty years in the wilderness?',
   'ἔστρεψεν δὲ ὁ Θεὸς καὶ παρέδωκεν αὐτοὺς λατρεύειν τῇ στρατιᾷ τοῦ οὐρανοῦ, καθὼς γέγραπται ἐν βίβλῳ προφητῶν, Μὴ σφάγια καὶ θυσίας προσηνέγκατέ μοι ἔτη τεσσαράκοντα ἐν τῇ ἐρήμῳ, οἶκος Ἰσραήλ;',
   'estrepsen de ho Theos kai paredōken autous latreuein tē stratiā tou ouranou, kathōs gegraptai en biblō prophētōn, Mē sphagia kai thysias prosēnenkaté moi etē tessarakonta en tē erēmō, oikos Israēl?',
   'Stephen quotes Amos 5:25-27, stating that ''God turned, and gave them up to worship the host of heaven.'' This divine judgment of ''giving them up'' to their idolatry is a severe consequence of their rebellion. The rhetorical question from Amos, ''Have ye offered to me slain beasts and sacrifices by the space of forty years in the wilderness, O ye house of Israel?'' implies that their worship during that period was often insincere or mixed with idolatry, not solely directed to God.',
   'This verse reveals a profound theological truth: God''s judgment can manifest as ''giving them up'' to their chosen idolatry. When people persistently reject Him, God may allow them to pursue their false gods, leading to deeper spiritual bondage. The quote from Amos challenges the assumption that outward religious acts (sacrifices) are sufficient without genuine heart-worship, highlighting the spiritual nature of true devotion.'),
  (43,
   'Yea, ye took up the tabernacle of Moloch, and the star of your god Remphan, figures which ye made to worship them: and I will carry you away beyond Babylon.',
   'καὶ ἀνελάβετε τὴν σκηνὴν τοῦ Μολὸχ καὶ τὸ ἄστρον τοῦ θεοῦ ὑμῶν Ῥομφάν, τοὺς τύπους οὓς ἐποιήσατε προσκυνεῖν αὐτοῖς· καὶ μετοικιῶ ὑμᾶς ἐπέκεινα Βαβυλῶνος.',
   'kai anelabete tēn skēnēn tou Moloch kai to astron tou theou hymōn Romphan, tous typous hous epoiēsate proskynein autois; kai metoikiō hymas epekeina Babylōnos.',
   'Continuing the quote from Amos 5:26-27, Stephen accuses Israel of carrying ''the tabernacle of Moloch, and the star of your god Remphan'' (or Rephan, a variant of Saturn). These were pagan deities worshipped by the Israelites, even during their wilderness journey. The consequence of this idolatry is God''s judgment: ''I will carry you away beyond Babylon.'' Stephen uses this prophecy to remind his audience of their ancestors'' persistent idolatry and the resulting exile, connecting past judgment to their present spiritual state.',
   'This verse exposes the pervasive nature of idolatry within Israel''s history, even during the wilderness period. The worship of Moloch and Remphan represents a deep spiritual compromise and syncretism. God''s response, ''I will carry you away beyond Babylon,'' demonstrates that persistent idolatry leads to divine judgment and exile, underscoring the seriousness of unfaithfulness to the one true God.'),
  (44,
   'Our fathers had the tabernacle of witness in the wilderness, as he had appointed, speaking unto Moses, that he should make it according to the fashion that he had seen.',
   'Ἡ σκηνὴ τοῦ μαρτυρίου ἦν τοῖς πατράσιν ἡμῶν ἐν τῇ ἐρήμῳ, καθὼς διετάξατο ὁ λαλῶν τῷ Μωϋσῇ ποιῆσαι αὐτὴν κατὰ τὸν τύπον ὃν ἑωράκει·',
   'Hē skēnē tou martyríou ēn tois patrasin hēmōn en tē erēmō, kathōs dietaxato ho lalōn tō Mōysē poiēsai autēn kata ton typon hon heōrakei;',
   'Stephen now shifts to the ''tabernacle of witness'' (or ''tent of testimony''), emphasizing its divine origin and temporary nature. It was made ''according to the fashion that he had seen'' (Exodus 25:9, 40), meaning it was a copy of a heavenly pattern. This highlights that even the most sacred structure was not an end in itself but a divinely ordained symbol. This prepares for his argument that God''s presence is not confined to man-made structures.',
   'The ''tabernacle of witness'' (σκηνὴ τοῦ μαρτυρίου) was a divinely appointed, portable sanctuary, built ''according to the fashion that he had seen'' (κατὰ τὸν τύπον ὃν ἑωράκει). This emphasizes its heavenly origin and symbolic nature, serving as a temporary dwelling for God''s presence among His people. It foreshadows the ultimate dwelling of God among humanity in Christ (John 1:14) and challenges the notion that God''s presence is limited to fixed, earthly structures.'),
  (45,
   'Which also our fathers that came after brought in with Jesus into the possession of the Gentiles, whom God drave out before the face of our fathers, unto the days of David;',
   'ἣν καὶ εἰσήγαγον διαδεξάμενοι οἱ πατέρες ἡμῶν μετὰ Ἰησοῦ ἐν τῇ κατασχέσει τῶν ἐθνῶν, ὧν ἐξῶσεν ὁ Θεὸς ἀπὸ προσώπου τῶν πατέρων ἡμῶν, ἕως τῶν ἡμερῶν Δαυίδ·',
   'Hēn kai eisēgagon diadexaménoi hoi pateres hēmōn meta Iēsou en tē kataschesei tōn ethnōn, hōn exōsen ho Theos apo prosōpou tōn paterōn hēmōn, heōs tōn hēmerōn Dauid;',
   'Stephen states that ''our fathers that came after brought in'' the tabernacle ''with Jesus'' (Joshua) into the possession of the Gentiles (Canaanites), whom God drove out. This continues the historical narrative, showing the tabernacle''s journey through the conquest of Canaan ''unto the days of David.'' This emphasizes the tabernacle''s mobile nature and its role during the period of judges and early kings, before the temple was built.',
   NULL),
  (46,
   'Who found favour before God, and desired to find a tabernacle for the God of Jacob.',
   'ὃς εὗρεν χάριν ἐνώπιον τοῦ Θεοῦ καὶ ᾐτήσατο εὑρεῖν σκήνωμα τῷ Θεῷ Ἰακώβ.',
   'hos heuren charin enōpion tou Theou kai ēitēsato heurein skēnōma tō Theō Iakōb.',
   'David ''found favour before God'' and ''desired to find a tabernacle for the God of Jacob'' (2 Samuel 7:1-3; Psalm 132:4-5). This highlights David''s piety and his desire to build a permanent dwelling place for God. Stephen acknowledges David''s good intentions, setting up the contrast with Solomon, who actually built the temple, and ultimately with God''s true dwelling place.',
   NULL),
  (47,
   'But Solomon built him an house.',
   'Σολομὼν δὲ οἰκοδόμησεν αὐτῷ οἶκον.',
   'Solomōn de oikodomēsen autō oikon.',
   'Stephen states simply, ''But Solomon built him an house'' (1 Kings 6:1-38). This marks the transition from the mobile tabernacle to the fixed temple. While acknowledging the temple''s construction, Stephen immediately moves to qualify its significance, preparing his audience for his radical theological assertion about God''s true dwelling place.',
   NULL),
  (48,
   'Howbeit the most High dwelleth not in temples made with hands; as saith the prophet,',
   'Ἀλλ’ οὐχ ὁ ὕψιστος ἐν χειροποιήτοις κατοικεῖ, καθὼς ὁ προφήτης λέγει,',
   'All'' ouch ho hypsistos en cheiropoiētois katoikei, kathōs ho prophētēs legei,',
   'This is a pivotal statement in Stephen''s defense: ''Howbeit the most High dwelleth not in temples made with hands.'' This directly challenges the Sanhedrin''s over-reliance on the physical temple as the exclusive dwelling place of God. Stephen asserts God''s transcendence, quoting Isaiah to support his claim. This is a direct refutation of the charge that he spoke against the temple (Acts 6:13-14), by redefining God''s presence.',
   'This is a foundational theological declaration: ''the most High dwelleth not in temples made with hands.'' Stephen challenges the misconception that God''s presence is confined to human-built structures. This truth, rooted in Old Testament prophecy, underscores God''s transcendence and omnipresence, preparing the way for understanding Christ as the true temple (John 2:19-21) and the Holy Spirit dwelling in believers (1 Cor 6:19).'),
  (49,
   'Heaven is my throne, and earth is my footstool: what house will ye build me? saith the Lord: or what is the place of my rest?',
   'Ὁ οὐρανός μοι θρόνος, ἡ δὲ γῆ ὑποπόδιον τῶν ποδῶν μου· ποῖον οἶκον οἰκοδομήσετέ μοι, λέγει Κύριος, ἢ τίς τόπος τῆς καταπαύσεώς μου;',
   'Ho ouranos moi thronos, hē de gē hypopodion tōn podōn mou; poion oikon oikodomēsete moi, legei Kyrios, ē tis topos tēs katapauseōs mou?',
   'Stephen quotes Isaiah 66:1-2: ''Heaven is my throne, and earth is my footstool: what house will ye build me? saith the Lord: or what is the place of my rest?'' This prophetic passage powerfully emphasizes God''s infinite majesty and His inability to be contained by any human-made structure. It reinforces the idea that true worship is not bound by physical location but by a spiritual reality, directly undermining the temple''s ultimate significance.',
   'Quoting Isaiah 66:1-2, Stephen asserts God''s infinite transcendence and omnipresence. If ''Heaven is my throne, and earth is my footstool,'' then no human-built ''house'' can contain or define Him. This challenges any anthropocentric view of God and any exclusive claim to His presence based on physical structures, emphasizing that God''s true dwelling is spiritual and universal, not confined to a temple.'),
  (50,
   'Hath not my hand made all these things?',
   'οὐχὶ ἡ χείρ μου ἐποίησεν ταῦτα πάντα;',
   'ouchi hē cheir mou epoiēsen tauta panta?',
   'The rhetorical question, ''Hath not my hand made all these things?'' (Isaiah 66:2), concludes Stephen''s argument about God''s transcendence. It asserts God''s sole creative power over all things, including the heavens and the earth. This implies that the Creator cannot be limited by His creation, nor can He be served by human hands as if He needed anything (Acts 17:24-25). This is a direct challenge to the Sanhedrin''s temple-centric theology.',
   'This rhetorical question affirms God''s absolute sovereignty as Creator of ''all these things.'' It underscores His self-sufficiency and independence from human constructs or services. The Creator is not confined by His creation, nor does He require anything from human hands. This truth dismantles any notion that God is dependent on the temple or human rituals, redirecting worship to the transcendent Creator alone.'),
  (51,
   'Ye stiffnecked and uncircumcised in heart and ears, ye do always resist the Holy Ghost: as your fathers did, so do ye.',
   'Σκληροτράχηλοι καὶ ἀπερίτμητοι καρδίαις καὶ τοῖς ὠσίν, ὑμεῖς ἀεὶ τῷ Πνεύματι τῷ Ἁγίῳ ἀντιπίπτετε, ὡς οἱ πατέρες ὑμῶν καὶ ὑμεῖς.',
   'Sklērotrachēloi kai aperitmētoi kardiāis kai tois ōsin, hymeis aei tō Pneumati tō Hagiō antipiptete, hōs hoi pateres hymōn kai hymeis.',
   'Stephen abruptly shifts from historical narrative to a direct, fiery accusation: ''Ye stiffnecked and uncircumcised in heart and ears, ye do always resist the Holy Ghost: as your fathers did, so do ye.'' ''Stiffnecked'' (σκληροτράχηλοι) is an Old Testament idiom for stubborn rebellion (Exodus 32:9). ''Uncircumcised in heart and ears'' (ἀπερίτμητοι καρδίαις καὶ τοῖς ὠσίν) is a profound spiritual indictment, contrasting with the physical circumcision they valued. It means they are spiritually deaf and unreceptive to God''s truth, perpetually resisting the Holy Spirit, just like their ancestors. This is the climax of his argument, directly accusing them of the very resistance he documented throughout Israel''s history.',
   'This verse contains a powerful indictment against spiritual stubbornness and resistance to God. The terms ''stiffnecked'' and ''uncircumcised in heart and ears'' denote a profound spiritual insensitivity and rebellion against divine truth. Stephen accuses his audience of perpetually ''resist[ing] the Holy Ghost,'' highlighting that opposition to God''s messengers and truth is ultimately opposition to the Spirit Himself. This reveals a continuity of spiritual rebellion from their ancestors to the present generation.'),
  (52,
   'Which of the prophets have not your fathers persecuted? and they have slain them which shewed before of the coming of the Just One; of whom ye have been now the betrayers and murderers:',
   'Τίνα τῶν προφητῶν οὐκ ἐδίωξαν οἱ πατέρες ὑμῶν; καὶ ἀπέκτειναν τοὺς προκαταγγείλαντας περὶ τῆς ἐλεύσεως τοῦ Δικαίου, οὗ νῦν ὑμεῖς προδόται καὶ φονεῖς ἐγένεσθε·',
   'Tina tōn prophētōn ouk ediōxan hoi pateres hymōn? kai apekteinan tous prokatangeilantas peri tēs eleuseōs tou Dikaiou, hou nyn hymeis prodotai kai phoneis egenesthe;',
   'Stephen continues his accusation, asking rhetorically, ''Which of the prophets have not your fathers persecuted?'' He then directly links this historical pattern to their present sin: ''and they have slain them which shewed before of the coming of the Just One; of whom ye have been now the betrayers and murderers.'' ''The Just One'' (τοῦ Δικαίου) is a clear reference to Jesus Christ (Acts 3:14; 22:14). Stephen accuses them of fulfilling the pattern of their ancestors by betraying and murdering the Messiah, the ultimate prophet.',
   'This verse is a direct Christological accusation. Stephen links the historical persecution of prophets, who foretold the Messiah''s coming, to the Sanhedrin''s recent actions. By calling Jesus ''the Just One'' (τοῦ Δικαίου) and accusing them of being His ''betrayers and murderers,'' Stephen declares their ultimate guilt in rejecting God''s final and most perfect messenger. This highlights humanity''s persistent sin of rejecting divine revelation, culminating in the crucifixion of Christ.'),
  (53,
   'Who have received the law by the disposition of angels, and have not kept it.',
   'οἵτινες ἐλάβετε τὸν νόμον εἰς διαταγὰς ἀγγέλων, καὶ οὐκ ἐφυλάξατε.',
   'hoitines elabete ton nomon eis diatagas angelōn, kai ouk ephulaxate.',
   'Stephen concludes his indictment by reminding them that they ''received the law by the disposition of angels'' (referring to the angelic mediation at Sinai, Galatians 3:19; Hebrews 2:2), ''and have not kept it.'' This is the ultimate charge: despite receiving the Law through divine means and valuing it highly, they failed to obey it. Their hypocrisy and spiritual blindness are fully exposed, justifying Stephen''s earlier arguments about God''s transcendence over man-made institutions and their own history of rebellion.',
   'This final charge exposes the hypocrisy of Stephen''s accusers: they prided themselves on possessing the Law, which they received through angelic mediation, yet they ''have not kept it.'' This highlights the inadequacy of merely possessing divine revelation without genuine obedience. It underscores the spiritual failure of relying on external adherence to the Law while rejecting its ultimate fulfillment in Christ and resisting the Holy Spirit, revealing the need for a new covenant of grace.'),
  (54,
   'When they heard these things, they were cut to the heart, and they gnashed on him with their teeth.',
   'Ἀκούοντες δὲ ταῦτα διεπρίοντο ταῖς καρδίαις αὐτῶν καὶ ἔβρυχον τοὺς ὀδόντας ἐπ’ αὐτόν.',
   'Akouontes de tauta dieprionto tais kardiāis autōn kai ebrychon tous odontas ep'' auton.',
   'Stephen''s words had a visceral effect: ''When they heard these things, they were cut to the heart, and they gnashed on him with their teeth.'' This intense reaction indicates extreme rage and indignation, not conviction. The phrase ''cut to the heart'' (διεπρίοντο ταῖς καρδίαις) implies being sawn asunder, a metaphor for excruciating anger. Their gnashing of teeth signifies uncontrollable fury, foreshadowing their violent response.',
   NULL),
  (55,
   'But he, being full of the Holy Ghost, looked up stedfastly into heaven, and saw the glory of God, and Jesus standing on the right hand of God,',
   'ὑπάρχων δὲ πλήρης Πνεύματος Ἁγίου ἀτενίσας εἰς τὸν οὐρανὸν εἶδεν δόξαν Θεοῦ καὶ Ἰησοῦν ἑστῶτα ἐκ δεξιῶν τοῦ Θεοῦ,',
   'hyparchōn de plērēs Pneumatos Hagiou atenisas eis ton ouranon eiden doxan Theou kai Iēsoun hestōta ek dexiōn tou Theou,',
   'In stark contrast to their rage, Stephen, ''being full of the Holy Ghost,'' looked ''stedfastly into heaven'' and ''saw the glory of God, and Jesus standing on the right hand of God.'' This vision is a divine affirmation of Stephen''s message and a powerful revelation of Christ''s exalted status. Jesus ''standing'' (ἑστῶτα) is notable; typically, He is depicted as seated at God''s right hand (Hebrews 10:12). His standing may signify His readiness to receive Stephen or to act on his behalf.',
   'This verse is a profound Christological and pneumatological affirmation. Stephen, ''full of the Holy Ghost,'' receives a divine vision of ''the glory of God, and Jesus standing on the right hand of God.'' This confirms Jesus'' exalted divine status and His active intercession or readiness to receive Stephen. It demonstrates the Holy Spirit''s role in revealing Christ''s glory and empowering believers in the face of persecution, offering a glimpse into heavenly realities.'),
  (56,
   'And said, Behold, I see the heavens opened, and the Son of man standing on the right hand of God.',
   'καὶ εἶπεν, Ἰδοὺ θεωρῶ τοὺς οὐρανοὺς ἀνεῳγμένους καὶ τὸν Υἱὸν τοῦ ἀνθρώπου ἐκ δεξιῶν ἑστῶτα τοῦ Θεοῦ.',
   'kai eipen, Idou theōrō tous ouranous aneōgmenous kai ton Huion tou anthrōpou ek dexiōn hestōta tou Theou.',
   'Stephen proclaims his vision: ''Behold, I see the heavens opened, and the Son of man standing on the right hand of God.'' The title ''Son of man'' (Υἱὸν τοῦ ἀνθρώπου), used by Jesus to refer to Himself (Daniel 7:13-14), is a powerful messianic claim, emphasizing both His humanity and His divine authority as the heavenly judge. This public declaration of Jesus'' divine exaltation further enraged the Sanhedrin, who considered it blasphemy.',
   'Stephen''s declaration of seeing ''the heavens opened, and the Son of man standing on the right hand of God'' is a direct affirmation of Jesus'' messianic identity and divine authority. The title ''Son of man'' (Υἱὸν τοῦ ἀνθρώπου) evokes Daniel 7:13-14, portraying Christ as the exalted, heavenly judge. This vision serves as a powerful testimony to Jesus'' resurrection and ascension, confirming His ultimate sovereignty and Stephen''s faith in Him.'),
  (57,
   'Then they cried out with a loud voice, and stopped their ears, and ran upon him with one accord,',
   'Κράξαντες δὲ φωνῇ μεγάλῃ συνέσχον τὰ ὦτα αὐτῶν καὶ ὥρμησαν ὁμοθυμαδὸν ἐπ’ αὐτόν,',
   'Kraxantes de phōnē megalē syneschon ta ōta autōn kai hōrmēsan homothymadon ep'' auton,',
   'Their reaction to Stephen''s vision was immediate and violent: ''Then they cried out with a loud voice, and stopped their ears, and ran upon him with one accord.'' Stopping their ears was a symbolic act of rejecting what they considered blasphemy (Leviticus 24:16). Their unified, frenzied attack (''ran upon him with one accord'') demonstrates their complete loss of control and their determination to silence Stephen, mirroring the rejection of Jesus.',
   NULL),
  (58,
   'And cast him out of the city, and stoned him: and the witnesses laid down their clothes at a young man’s feet, whose name was Saul.',
   'καὶ ἐκβαλόντες ἔξω τῆς πόλεως ἐλιθοβόλουν. καὶ οἱ μάρτυρες ἀπέθεντο τὰ ἱμάτια αὐτῶν παρὰ τοὺς πόδας νεανίου καλουμένου Σαύλου.',
   'kai ekbalontes exō tēs poleōs elithoboloun. kai hoi martyres apethento ta himatia autōn para tous podas neaniou kaloumenou Saoulou.',
   'They ''cast him out of the city, and stoned him.'' Stoning was the prescribed punishment for blasphemy (Leviticus 24:16). The detail that ''the witnesses laid down their clothes at a young man’s feet, whose name was Saul,'' is highly significant. This introduces Saul (later Paul) into the narrative, showing his active participation and approval of Stephen''s martyrdom. This moment sets the stage for Saul''s dramatic conversion and future role in spreading the very faith he now persecutes.',
   'This verse marks the first Christian martyrdom, demonstrating the ultimate cost of bearing witness to Christ. The detail of ''Saul'' (later Paul) guarding the cloaks of the witnesses is profoundly significant. It highlights the intense opposition faced by early Christians and providentially introduces the future apostle, whose conversion would dramatically shift the trajectory of early church history, showcasing God''s power to transform persecutors into fervent evangelists.'),
  (59,
   'And they stoned Stephen, calling upon God, and saying, Lord Jesus, receive my spirit.',
   'καὶ ἐλιθοβόλουν τὸν Στέφανον ἐπικαλούμενον καὶ λέγοντα, Κύριε Ἰησοῦ, δέξαι τὸ πνεῦμά μου.',
   'kai elithoboloun ton Stephanon epikaloumenon kai legonta, Kyrie Iēsou, dexai to pneuma mou.',
   'As they stoned him, Stephen called upon God, saying, ''Lord Jesus, receive my spirit.'' This echoes Jesus'' own words on the cross (Luke 23:46). Stephen''s direct prayer to Jesus demonstrates his profound faith in Christ''s divinity and His ability to receive his spirit. This act of worship, directed to Jesus, further solidified the early church''s understanding of Jesus'' divine nature and His role as the exalted Lord.',
   'Stephen''s dying prayer, ''Lord Jesus, receive my spirit,'' is a profound theological statement. It demonstrates his unwavering faith in Jesus'' divinity and His authority to receive the spirits of the departed. This direct invocation of Jesus as Lord, mirroring Christ''s own words on the cross, serves as a powerful testament to the early church''s understanding of Jesus as God and the object of worship, even in the face of death.'),
  (60,
   'And he kneeled down, and cried with a loud voice, Lord, lay not this sin to their charge. And when he had said this, he fell asleep.',
   'θεὶς δὲ τὰ γόνατα ἔκραξεν φωνῇ μεγάλῃ, Κύριε, μὴ στήσῃς αὐτοῖς ταύτην τὴν ἁμαρτίαν. καὶ τοῦτο εἰπὼν ἐκοιμήθη.',
   'theis de ta gonata ekraxen phōnē megalē, Kyrie, mē stēsēis autois tautēn tēn hamartian. kai touto eipōn ekoimēthē.',
   'Stephen''s final words, ''Lord, lay not this sin to their charge,'' spoken while kneeling, echo Jesus'' prayer for His persecutors (Luke 23:34). This act of forgiveness in the face of brutal violence exemplifies Christ-like love and grace. The phrase ''he fell asleep'' (ἐκοιμήθη) is a common biblical euphemism for death, particularly for believers, signifying peace and the hope of resurrection. Stephen''s martyrdom, marked by Christ-like forgiveness, became a powerful witness.',
   'Stephen''s final act of forgiveness, ''Lord, lay not this sin to their charge,'' mirrors Christ''s own prayer on the cross (Luke 23:34) and exemplifies the transformative power of the Gospel. It demonstrates the profound love and grace that characterize true discipleship, even in the face of extreme persecution. His peaceful ''falling asleep'' underscores the Christian hope in resurrection and the ultimate triumph over death through Christ.')
) AS v(verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
WHERE b.name = 'Acts' AND c.chapter_number = 7;

-- Step 3: Word Studies for key verses

-- Verse 2
INSERT INTO word_studies (verse_id, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
SELECT v.id, ws.original_word, ws.transliteration, ws.strongs_number, ws.meaning, ws.word_order
FROM verses v
JOIN chapters c ON v.chapter_id = c.id
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  ('δόξης', 'doxēs', 'G1391', 'From ''dokeō'' (to think, seem), meaning ''glory,'' ''splendor,'' ''honor,'' or ''majesty.'' In this context, ''The God of glory'' refers to God''s inherent majesty and radiant presence, emphasizing His transcendent nature and the awe-inspiring manifestation of His being. It signifies His divine essence and the visible manifestation of His power and holiness.', 1),
  ('ὤφθη', 'ōphthē', 'G3700', 'Aorist passive of ''horaō'' (to see), meaning ''he appeared'' or ''he was seen.'' It denotes a divine manifestation or revelation, often implying a supernatural encounter. Stephen uses it to highlight God''s initiative in revealing Himself to Abraham, underscoring that God actively intervenes in human history through visible manifestations of His presence.', 2),
  ('πατρὶ', 'patri', 'G3962', 'From ''patēr'' (father), meaning ''father'' or ''ancestor.'' Here, ''our father Abraham'' emphasizes the foundational role of Abraham in Israel''s lineage and covenant history. Stephen uses this term to connect with his Jewish audience, affirming their shared heritage while subtly reinterpreting its significance in light of God''s broader plan.', 3)
) AS ws(original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
WHERE b.name = 'Acts' AND c.chapter_number = 7 AND v.verse_number = 2;

-- Verse 8
INSERT INTO word_studies (verse_id, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
SELECT v.id, ws.original_word, ws.transliteration, ws.strongs_number, ws.meaning, ws.word_order
FROM verses v
JOIN chapters c ON v.chapter_id = c.id
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  ('διαθήκην', 'diathēkēn', 'G1242', 'From ''diatithēmi'' (to arrange, dispose), meaning ''covenant,'' ''testament,'' or ''agreement.'' It refers to a solemn, binding agreement, especially one initiated by God with humanity. The ''covenant of circumcision'' was a physical sign of God''s promise to Abraham and his descendants, marking them as His chosen people and signifying a relationship of mutual obligation and promise.', 1),
  ('περιτομῆς', 'peritomēs', 'G4061', 'From ''peritemnō'' (to cut around), meaning ''circumcision.'' This physical ritual was the sign of the Abrahamic covenant, symbolizing the cutting away of the flesh and dedication to God. Stephen''s mention acknowledges its historical importance while later contrasting it with the ''circumcision of the heart'' (v. 51), highlighting a shift from external ritual to internal spiritual reality.', 2),
  ('πατριάρχας', 'patriarchas', 'G3966', 'From ''patria'' (family, lineage) and ''archō'' (to rule), meaning ''patriarch'' or ''head of a family/tribe.'' It refers to the twelve sons of Jacob, who were the progenitors of the twelve tribes of Israel. Stephen uses this term to trace the lineage of God''s chosen people, emphasizing their foundational role in Israel''s history and the continuity of God''s covenant promises through them.', 3)
) AS ws(original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
WHERE b.name = 'Acts' AND c.chapter_number = 7 AND v.verse_number = 8;

-- Verse 35
INSERT INTO word_studies (verse_id, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
SELECT v.id, ws.original_word, ws.transliteration, ws.strongs_number, ws.meaning, ws.word_order
FROM verses v
JOIN chapters c ON v.chapter_id = c.id
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  ('ἠρνήσαντο', 'ērnēsanto', 'G720', 'Aorist middle of ''arneomai'' (to deny, reject, refuse). It signifies a deliberate act of disowning or repudiating. Stephen uses this to highlight Israel''s historical pattern of rejecting God''s chosen leaders, specifically Moses, despite his divine appointment. This foreshadows their rejection of Jesus, the ultimate deliverer.', 1),
  ('ἄρχοντα', 'archonta', 'G758', 'From ''archō'' (to rule), meaning ''ruler,'' ''leader,'' or ''magistrate.'' It denotes one who holds authority and exercises governance. Stephen emphasizes that God sent Moses as a divinely appointed ''ruler,'' contrasting with the people''s question, ''Who made thee a ruler?'' This underscores God''s sovereignty in appointing leaders, regardless of human acceptance.', 2),
  ('λυτρωτὴν', 'lytrōtēn', 'G3086', 'From ''lytroō'' (to redeem, set free), meaning ''redeemer'' or ''deliverer.'' It refers to one who pays a ransom or liberates from bondage. Stephen highlights Moses'' role as God''s instrument for delivering Israel from Egyptian slavery. This term is highly significant as it prefigures Jesus Christ as the ultimate ''Redeemer'' from sin and death.', 3)
) AS ws(original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
WHERE b.name = 'Acts' AND c.chapter_number = 7 AND v.verse_number = 35;

-- Verse 38
INSERT INTO word_studies (verse_id, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
SELECT v.id, ws.original_word, ws.transliteration, ws.strongs_number, ws.meaning, ws.word_order
FROM verses v
JOIN chapters c ON v.chapter_id = c.id
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  ('ἐκκλησίᾳ', 'ekklēsiā', 'G1577', 'From ''ekkaléō'' (to call out), meaning ''assembly,'' ''congregation,'' or ''church.'' Here, it refers to the assembly of Israel in the wilderness, emphasizing their corporate identity as God''s called-out people. Stephen''s use of this term suggests a continuity between Old Testament Israel and the New Testament church, highlighting God''s consistent purpose for His people.', 1),
  ('λόγια', 'logia', 'G3051', 'Plural of ''logion'' (a divine utterance, oracle). It refers to the sacred utterances or revelations of God, specifically the Law given to Moses at Sinai. Stephen describes them as ''lively oracles'' (λόγια ζῶντα), emphasizing their divine origin, life-giving power, and enduring truth, which were meant to guide and sustain God''s people.', 2),
  ('ζῶντα', 'zōnta', 'G2198', 'Present participle of ''zaō'' (to live), meaning ''living,'' ''alive,'' or ''life-giving.'' When applied to ''oracles'' (λόγια), it emphasizes their dynamic, active, and vital nature. The Law given through Moses was not merely a set of rules but a living word from God, intended to bring life and guide His people into a vibrant relationship with Him.', 3)
) AS ws(original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
WHERE b.name = 'Acts' AND c.chapter_number = 7 AND v.verse_number = 38;

-- Verse 51
INSERT INTO word_studies (verse_id, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
SELECT v.id, ws.original_word, ws.transliteration, ws.strongs_number, ws.meaning, ws.word_order
FROM verses v
JOIN chapters c ON v.chapter_id = c.id
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  ('Σκληροτράχηλοι', 'Sklērotrachēloi', 'G4644', 'From ''sklēros'' (hard) and ''trachēlos'' (neck), meaning ''stiffnecked'' or ''hard-necked.'' This is an Old Testament idiom (e.g., Ex 32:9) describing stubbornness, obstinacy, and resistance to God''s will. Stephen uses it to accuse his audience of their persistent rebellion, mirroring their ancestors'' refusal to submit to divine authority.', 1),
  ('ἀπερίτμητοι', 'aperitmētoi', 'G564', 'From ''a'' (not) and ''peritemnō'' (to circumcise), meaning ''uncircumcised.'' While physically circumcised, Stephen uses it metaphorically to mean ''uncircumcised in heart and ears,'' signifying spiritual insensitivity, deafness to God''s word, and an unrepentant heart. It implies a lack of true spiritual separation and dedication to God, despite outward religious observance.', 2),
  ('ἀντιπίπτετε', 'antipiptete', 'G496', 'From ''anti'' (against) and ''piptō'' (to fall), meaning ''to fall against,'' ''to resist,'' or ''to oppose.'' Stephen uses this to accuse his audience of perpetually ''resist[ing] the Holy Ghost.'' It denotes active, willful opposition to divine influence and truth, highlighting a continuous pattern of rebellion against God''s Spirit and His messengers throughout Israel''s history.', 3),
  ('Πνεύματι', 'Pneumati', 'G4151', 'From ''pneō'' (to breathe), meaning ''spirit,'' ''wind,'' or ''breath.'' Here, ''the Holy Ghost'' (τῷ Πνεύματι τῷ Ἁγίῳ) refers to the third person of the Trinity, the divine Spirit of God. Stephen''s accusation that they ''always resist the Holy Ghost'' underscores that their opposition to God''s truth and messengers is ultimately opposition to God Himself.', 4)
) AS ws(original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
WHERE b.name = 'Acts' AND c.chapter_number = 7 AND v.verse_number = 51;

-- Verse 52
INSERT INTO word_studies (verse_id, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
SELECT v.id, ws.original_word, ws.transliteration, ws.strongs_number, ws.meaning, ws.word_order
FROM verses v
JOIN chapters c ON v.chapter_id = c.id
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  ('προφητῶν', 'prophētōn', 'G4396', 'From ''pro'' (before) and ''phēmi'' (to speak), meaning ''prophet'' or ''one who speaks forth.'' It refers to God''s messengers who declared His will, often foretelling future events. Stephen highlights Israel''s historical persecution of these prophets, establishing a pattern of rejecting divine revelation and those who delivered it, culminating in the rejection of Christ.', 1),
  ('Δικαίου', 'Dikaiou', 'G1342', 'From ''dikē'' (right, justice), meaning ''just,'' ''righteous,'' or ''innocent.'' Here, ''the Just One'' (τοῦ Δικαίου) is a messianic title for Jesus Christ, emphasizing His perfect righteousness and blamelessness. Stephen uses this title to underscore the profound injustice of His betrayal and murder, contrasting His perfect character with the unrighteousness of His persecutors.', 2),
  ('προδόται', 'prodotai', 'G4273', 'From ''prodidōmi'' (to give over, betray), meaning ''betrayers'' or ''traitors.'' Stephen directly accuses his audience of being ''betrayers'' of the Just One, Jesus. This term highlights the act of handing over someone to an enemy, emphasizing the treachery involved in their role in Christ''s crucifixion, aligning them with Judas Iscariot.', 3),
  ('φονεῖς', 'phoneis', 'G5406', 'From ''phonos'' (murder), meaning ''murderers.'' Stephen''s accusation that they are ''murderers'' of the Just One is a direct and severe charge, holding them responsible for Christ''s death. This term underscores the gravity of their sin and their active participation in the ultimate act of rejecting God''s Son.', 4)
) AS ws(original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
WHERE b.name = 'Acts' AND c.chapter_number = 7 AND v.verse_number = 52;

-- Verse 55
INSERT INTO word_studies (verse_id, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
SELECT v.id, ws.original_word, ws.transliteration, ws.strongs_number, ws.meaning, ws.word_order
FROM verses v
JOIN chapters c ON v.chapter_id = c.id
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  ('πλήρης', 'plērēs', 'G4134', 'From ''plēroō'' (to fill), meaning ''full,'' ''complete,'' or ''abundant.'' Stephen is described as ''full of the Holy Ghost,'' indicating a complete saturation and empowerment by the Spirit. This state of spiritual fullness enabled him to see the heavenly vision and speak with divine authority, contrasting with the spiritual emptiness of his accusers.', 1),
  ('ἀτενίσας', 'atenisas', 'G816', 'From ''a'' (intensive) and ''teinō'' (to stretch), meaning ''to gaze intently,'' ''to fix one''s eyes upon,'' or ''to stare.'' Stephen''s ''stedfastly'' looking into heaven signifies focused attention and spiritual perception, enabled by the Holy Spirit, allowing him to perceive the divine glory and the exalted Christ, unseen by his earthly persecutors.', 2),
  ('ἑστῶτα', 'hestōta', 'G2476', 'Perfect active participle of ''histēmi'' (to stand), meaning ''standing.'' Jesus is typically depicted as ''seated'' at God''s right hand (Heb 10:12). His ''standing'' here is often interpreted as a posture of readiness to receive Stephen, to intercede, or to act as judge. It conveys an active, dynamic presence rather than a static, passive one, offering comfort and assurance to the dying martyr.', 3),
  ('δεξιῶν', 'dexiōn', 'G1188', 'From ''dexios'' (right), meaning ''right hand'' or ''right side.'' In biblical and ancient cultures, the right hand symbolizes power, authority, honor, and favor. Jesus ''standing on the right hand of God'' signifies His exalted position, sharing in God''s divine authority and majesty, confirming His supreme sovereignty and divine status.', 4)
) AS ws(original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
WHERE b.name = 'Acts' AND c.chapter_number = 7 AND v.verse_number = 55;

